This article discusses President Obama's efforts to ensure equal pay for women and promote the women's economic agenda. The article highlights the fact that women still earn 77 cents to every dollar earned by men, and many women are unaware that they are underpaid. To combat pay discrimination, President Obama is signing an Executive Order prohibiting federal contractors from retaliating against employees who discuss their compensation. He is also instructing the Secretary of Labor to establish new regulations requiring federal contractors to submit summary data on compensation paid to their employees, including data by sex and race. The article mentions that the Senate is considering the Paycheck Fairness Act, which the President believes Congress must pass to ensure equal pay standards are applied to all employers. The article also discusses other initiatives taken by the Obama Administration to combat pay discrimination, such as the Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act and the creation of a National Equal Pay Task Force. Additionally, the article mentions the President's efforts to raise the national minimum wage and expand the Earned Income Tax Credit for childless workers.